          "body": "The chapter opens with a category that modern religion tends to keep separate: civil fraud and religious guilt. In Leviticus 6:2 the LORD fuses them: sinning against a neighbor through a deposit gone missing, robbery, extortion, or a false oath is simultaneously 'acting unfaithfully against the LORD' (maal). The Hebrew word maal is the vocabulary of covenant treachery — the same word used of Israel's unfaithfulness in worshiping other gods (Ezekiel 14:13). There is no secular/sacred divide in the Mosaic framework. Every deceptive act against a covenant neighbor fractures one's standing before the holy God who constituted that neighborhood. This is why the guilt offering of verses 6-7 cannot precede restitution — the sacrifice addresses the vertical fracture, but it cannot be offered while the horizontal fracture (the defrauded neighbor) remains open. Jesus's instruction in Matthew 5:23-24 ('first be reconciled to your brother, and then come and present your offering') stands squarely in this tradition."
