        "title": "Guilt before neighbor and guilt before God are one — the restitution-sacrifice sequence",
        "range": "6:1-7",
        "excerpt": "When a person sins and acts unfaithfully against the LORD, and deceives his companion in regard to a deposit or a security entrusted to him, or through robbery, or if he has extorted from his companion…",
        "body": "The guilt-offering case study that opens chapter 6 completes the legislation begun at 5:14. But where 5:14-19 addressed unintentional sins against the LORD's holy things, 6:1-7 addresses deliberate wrongs against a neighbor — misappropriation, robbery, extortion, keeping found property, false swearing. The chapter's first interpretive surprise is the framing: these wrongs against a neighbor are simultaneously described as 'acting unfaithfully against the LORD' (maal, 6:2). The horizontal offense does not become a vertical one only when the offender takes it to the altar; it already is a vertical one the moment it is committed. Israel's covenant was structured so that every member of the community was under God's protection; to defraud a member was to attack what God had placed under His patronage.\n\nThe prescribed remedy has two irreducible phases. First, material restitution to the specific victim — the exact principal plus twenty percent (6:4-5). The one-fifth addition is not punitive; it is restorative, compensating for the economic harm of having been deprived of resources for an indeterminate period. Second, a guilt offering (asham) to the LORD — a ram without defect, assessed at a proper valuation (6:6). These two acts occur on the same day. The structural insistence on simultaneity is the text's way of saying that neither phase substitutes for the other. Sacrificial religion without prior repair of wrong is not accepted religion; material repair without sacrificial acknowledgment of the offense against God leaves the vertical debt unpaid.\n\nThe chapter's first climactic declaration is verse 7: 'and he will be forgiven.' The Hebrew salach appears here as a divine passive — God is the subject, the priest is the instrument ('the priest shall make atonement,' kipher, 6:7), and the outcome is the complete release of the offender from legal liability before the LORD. Three agents, one outcome: the offender confesses by bringing the animal, the priest makes atonement, God forgives. This triadic structure will recur throughout the sacrificial system and finds its antitypical resolution in 1 John 1:9 — the believer confesses, the High Priest (Christ) makes atonement, the faithful and righteous God forgives and cleanses.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maal* (unfaithfulness, 6:2) — covenant treachery; used of Israel's apostasy in Ezekiel 14:13 and Joshua 7:1 (Achan's taking of devoted things). *Kipher* (make atonement, 6:7) — from the root meaning 'to cover' or 'to wipe'; the Levitical system's central reconciliation verb, occurring over 100 times in Leviticus. *Salach* (forgiven, 6:7) — used exclusively of divine forgiveness in the OT; humans are never the subject. The combination of kipher (priestly act) + salach (divine act) is the system's irreducible two-movement resolution."
