        "title": "The fire that never goes out — unceasing access through continuous priestly labor",
        "range": "6:8-13",
        "excerpt": "The fire on the altar shall be kept burning on it. It shall not go out, but the priest shall burn wood on it every morning…Fire shall be kept burning continually on the altar; it is not to go out.",
        "body": "The burnt-offering regulations of verses 8-13 are dominated by one command stated three times: the altar fire must not go out (6:9, 12, 13). The triple repetition, unusual even in Leviticus, signals that this is the section's irreducible point. The fire was not man-made — it descended from the LORD at the altar's dedication (Leviticus 9:24), and its origin is what gives it theological significance. For the fire to go out would be for the divine-human point of contact to be broken, the altar rendered temporarily inoperative, and Israel's access to God interrupted. That must never happen.\n\nBut the perpetuity of the fire is not miraculous maintenance; it requires the priest to add wood every morning (6:12). This is the section's pastoral tension: the fire's origin is divine (not to be reproduced), but its continuation is human (not to be neglected). The priest who fails to add wood in the morning does not merely miss a procedural obligation — he allows the symbol of continuous divine-human mediation to die. Swindoll observes in his Leviticus commentary that the burnt-offering priest's role was inglorious by worldly standards: adding wood, removing ashes, changing garments to carry the ashes outside. The priestly dignity was not in the ceremony's visual drama but in the unfailing daily execution of tasks no one would notice until they were left undone.\n\nThe clothing change of verses 10-11 reinforces this theology. The priest wears his linen vestments — the garments of the sanctuary — to tend the altar ashes. But to carry those ashes outside the camp, he changes into 'other garments.' The distinction is not about contamination (the ashes are not defiling); it is about honor. The altar-clothing belongs to the altar; the removal of ashes to a clean place outside the camp is done in ordinary clothes, signaling that this humble task is performed at the margin of the sacred precinct, not at its center. Every detail of priestly dress in Leviticus is communicative — the garments tell the observers where they are in the sacred map.\n\nThe forward trajectory of this section is toward Hebrews 10:11-14. The Levitical priests 'stand daily ministering and offering time after time the same sacrifices, which can never take away sins.' The fire keeps burning because the work is never done; the wood keeps being added because the atonement is not finished. The Son of God, by contrast, 'offered one sacrifice for sins for all time' and 'sat down at the right hand of God.' The altar fire's perpetuity is not a symbol of completeness but of incompleteness — the very insistence that it never go out announces that the system requires continuous maintenance because it awaits a once-for-all offering that will make continuous maintenance unnecessary.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tamid* (continually, 6:13) — the same adverb used for the daily (tamid) burnt offering of Exodus 29:38-42 and the tamid lamp of Exodus 27:20. *Tamid* marks permanent, never-suspended institutions. *Yaqad* (kept burning) and *kavah* (be extinguished) are the chapter's fire-verbs — the positive command (keep it burning) and the negative prohibition (do not let it go out) work together to make extinction unthinkable."
