        "body": "The grain offering legislation of verses 14-23 divides into two parts with crucially different outcomes: the congregational grain offering (6:14-18), of which Aaron and his sons eat the remainder; and the priest's personal grain offering (6:19-23), which is burned entirely. The structural contrast is the section's theological payload.\n\nFor the congregational grain offering, the procedure is careful and specific: one handful is removed as the memorial portion (azkarah) and burned on the altar as a soothing aroma; the remainder is eaten by the male priests in the tabernacle court as unleavened cakes. The prohibition of leaven (6:17) is not arbitrary — leaven is the symbol of corruption spreading through a whole batch (cf. 1 Corinthians 5:6-8). The most holy food consumed by the mediators of the holy God must be free of the fermenting agent that pictures moral corruption. Verse 18 closes with the permanent-ordinance formula and a striking statement: 'Whoever touches them will become consecrated.' The holiness of the most holy grain offering is communicable — contact with it changes the one who touches it.\n\nThe priest's personal grain offering, however, operates by a completely different rule. Offered on the day of anointing and repeated daily thereafter (6:20), it is burned entirely — kalil, the whole-burnt-offering of completeness. The priest eats nothing of his own grain offering. This is the text's anti-clerical corrective: the one who administers others' atonement presents himself to God with complete, unpartitioned self-surrender. He keeps no portion for himself from his own offering. Peter Davids' observation about James's warning against double-mindedness applies here inversely — the priest's offering must not be divided between God and himself; it is wholly God's.\n\nCalvin recognized in this requirement a transparent testimony to the Levitical priesthood's anticipatory character. A priest who gives everything of his own offering and keeps nothing back points forward to the one High Priest who gave not a tenth of an ephah of flour but His own body — wholly, without remainder, entirely consumed in the act of mediation. Hebrews 7:27 names the fulfillment: unlike the Levitical high priests who 'offer up sacrifices daily, first for his own sins and then for the sins of the people,' the Son 'did this once for all when He offered up Himself.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Azkarah* (memorial portion, 6:15) — from zakar, 'to remember'; the portion burned on the altar that 'reminds' God of the whole offering and represents it. *Kalil* (entirely, completely, 6:22-23) — total consumption, no remainder; the same word used of the whole burnt offering in Deuteronomy 33:10. *Qodesh qodashim* (most holy, 6:17) — the superlative of holiness in Hebrew, reserved for the sin offering, guilt offering, and the inner sanctum furnishings."
