        "title": "The sin offering's most holy logic — eating, washing, breaking, burning",
        "range": "6:24-30",
        "excerpt": "This is the law of the sin offering: in the place where the burnt offering is slain the sin offering shall be slain before the LORD; it is most holy.",
        "body": "The sin offering regulations of verses 24-30 are the chapter's most detailed treatment of transmitted holiness. The sin offering (chattaah) is declared 'most holy' at the outset (6:25), and everything that follows flows from that designation. The slaughter location — the same spot where the burnt offering is killed (6:25) — grounds the sin offering in the altar's consecrated zone before a single drop of blood has been shed. The offering is most holy not because of what is done to it but because of what it is and what it accomplishes.\n\nVerse 26 assigns the flesh to the offering priest: 'The priest who offers it for sin shall eat it.' This is a striking provision. The sin offering priest personally consumes what he sacrifices. He does not hand it off to other priests; he is the one who eats it, in the holy court. Ancient Near Eastern parallels might suggest that eating sacred food communicated the deity's blessing; in the Levitical framework, the theology is more precise — the priest who mediates atonement between God and the sinning worshiper bears the sin offering's most holy substance into his own body, enacting in physical form the mediation he performs liturgically. The typological pointer is toward the one who did not merely eat the sin offering but became it — 'He made Him who knew no sin to be sin on our behalf' (2 Corinthians 5:21).\n\nVerses 27-28 detail the holiness-management protocols. Blood splattered on a garment must be washed in a holy place — the blood is too holy to be cleaned outside the sacred precinct. Earthenware vessels used to cook the sin offering must be broken and discarded — their porous surface has absorbed holiness so thoroughly that they cannot be returned to common use. Bronze vessels are scoured and rinsed — metal is non-porous and can be thoroughly purged. These distinctions are not squeamishness about blood or dirt; they are a material grammar of holiness. The sin offering's holiness is real, communicable, and consequential — it permanently marks what it touches.\n\nVerse 30 introduces the chapter's closing distinction and its most theologically charged regulation: if the sin offering's blood is brought into the tent of meeting — as on the Day of Atonement (Leviticus 16:27) — its flesh must be burned entirely; none of it may be eaten. The closer the blood's approach to the innermost holy presence of God, the more total the offering's consumption must be. Partial consumption is acceptable for sin offerings offered at the altar court; no consumption is acceptable for sin offerings whose blood enters the Holy Place. Proximity to the divine holiness intensifies the demand. The writer of Hebrews in 13:11-13 reads this typologically: the bodies of those animals whose blood was brought inside were burned outside the camp — and Jesus suffered outside the gate. The chapter's closing verse quietly points to Calvary.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nazah* (splashed/spattered, 6:27) — the same verb used for the sprinkling of blood in the Day of Atonement rite (Leviticus 16:14-15); the spatter is a kind of unintentional anointing. *Shavar* (broken, 6:28) — complete destruction; the same word used of breaking idols. *Saraph* (burned with fire, 6:30) — total destruction by fire; distinct from qatar (burn as incense/offering) used elsewhere in the chapter."
